    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "323975f6_19ed2b33",
        "filename": "util/ios/ios_system_data_collector.mm",
        "patchSetId": 16
      },
      "lineNbr": 88,
      "author": {
        "id": 1174099
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-03-25T00:41:50Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "\u003e It can only ever be x86_64?  systemsnapshotios already knows that at compile-time.\n\u003e \n\u003e I could expose interfaceidiom, but it\u0027s pretty analogous to what arm returns for uts.machine, so I figured I would mirror this here.\n\nOK, so this is just for SystemSnapshot::MachineDescription?\n\nWe do collect the same model string on macOS, for use in SystemSnapshot::MachineDescription. The meat of that is in MacModelAndBoard. We actually also collect the board information there, too. (Does MacModelAndBoard work on iOS? Recycle it!)\n\nIf utsname::machine does in fact do what you say on iOS, then you can use it. It’s just much less obvious, because utsname::machine on all other systems is the CPU name (on desktop macOS, it’s “x86_64”). That’s why I asked the question here: these strings you’re using for the simulator are not CPU names. It wasn’t obvious to me as a long-time user of uname that iOS would give back “iPhone10,3” here.\n\nBut I’d also say that the MacModelAndBoard are still relevant even in simulator cases, so I’d suggest merging the UI_USER_INTERFACE_IDIOM with the Mac model in simulator builds.",
      "parentUuid": "b1f70054_2e8265a4",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 79,
        "startChar": 0,
        "endLine": 88,
        "endChar": 0
      },
